<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  Decision <a href="/backlog/2265-relocate-agent-memory-skills-sot-out-of-claude-redirect-hook/">#2265</a>
  asks whether to relocate the <code>we:.claude/agent-memory/**</code> and <code>we:.claude/skills/**</code>
  source-of-truth <em>out</em> of <code>.claude/</code> (symlinked back, plus a personal
  <code>PreToolUse</code> redirect hook) so the Claude Code <code>.claude</code>-path permission gate
  auto-approves memory/skills edits — or keep <code>.claude</code> and defeat the unattended-workflow stall
  with <code>--dangerously-skip-permissions</code>. This is an <strong>agent-tooling / repo-layout</strong>
  call over the WE harness, not greenfield standard design, so there is no web-platform survey — the
  research is a consuming-tree read of the governed surfaces plus a statute-overlap check.
</p>

<h2>The verified mechanism</h2>
<p>
  The Claude Code VS Code extension hard-prompts on every edit whose literal path <strong>or realpath</strong>
  contains <code>/.claude/</code>, and nothing in config-land overrides it — the item's provenance verified
  <code>Edit()</code> allow rules (every path form), <code>additionalDirectories</code>, workspace
  membership, <code>acceptEdits</code>, project <code>bypassPermissions</code>, symlinks <em>into</em>
  <code>.claude</code>, and a <code>permissionDecision: "allow"</code> hook <em>all</em> fail to suppress it.
  Two levers do work (both verified 2026-07-04):
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Path-rewrite hook.</strong> A <code>PreToolUse</code> hook that rewrites a
    <code>.claude/(agent-memory|skills)/…</code> path to a real non-<code>.claude</code> path via
    <code>hookSpecificOutput.updatedInput.file_path</code> makes the gate classify the edit as
    non-<code>.claude</code> and auto-approve; the write lands on the real file.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Symlinked discovery.</strong> Claude Code follows a symlinked skill dir, so
    <code>we:.claude/skills</code> and <code>we:.claude/agent-memory</code> can be symlinks to an
    out-of-<code>.claude</code> SoT with discovery/loading intact.
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  The gate checks <strong>realpath</strong>, so a symlink <em>pointing into</em> <code>.claude</code> still
  prompts — the real files must physically leave <code>.claude</code>. This is a genuine SoT relocation, not
  just a hook.
</p>

<h2>Finding — the guard-lane exemption is realpath-keyed and breaks on relocation</h2>
<p>
  <code>we:scripts/guard-lane.mjs:56</code> exempts agent-memory from the "edits must run in a lane" block
  via a <code>real.includes()</code> test for the literal <code>.claude/agent-memory</code> segment — a
  <strong>realpath</strong> test. After a <code>git mv</code> to <code>we:agent-memory-src/</code> the
  realpath no longer contains that segment, so the exemption silently stops matching and primary-checkout
  memory edits would be blocked again. The memory slice <strong>must</strong> widen this exemption to also
  match <code>we:agent-memory-src</code> — the one non-mechanical code change on the memory side.
</p>

<h2>Finding (statute-overlap) — path citations must be reconciled, not just followed</h2>
<p>
  <code>we:docs/agent/platform-decisions.md:2488</code> cites <code>we:.claude/agent-memory/**</code> as the
  durable-content path that rides a <strong>lane→PR</strong> (with the
  <code>we:.claude/skills/batch-backlog-items/claims.json</code>-class <em>local signals</em> as the only
  sanctioned-direct carve-out, which "never widens to memory content"), and <code>:2379</code> lists a
  skills batch path as a ③ merge-risk mirror-home. These are <strong>transport / merge-risk</strong> rules
  keyed to a path <em>string</em>. Relocation makes the SoT path indirect (symlinked), but the rules are
  orthogonal to <em>where the file sits</em> and to <em>permission auto-approval</em> — auto-approving a
  local Edit is not a direct-<code>main</code> commit, so the lane→PR transport rule is
  <strong>unchanged</strong>. The ratifying change must amend the literal path citations (<code>:2488</code>,
  and <code>:2379</code> for the skills slice) to the new SoT path so the anchors don't read stale; the
  reconciliation is flagged now so ratification inherits no unreconciled statute conflict.
</p>

<h2>Finding — skills coupling is materially heavier than memory (the scope fork)</h2>
<p>
  A grep for the <code>we:.claude/skills/batch-backlog-items</code> state dir across <code>we:scripts/</code>
  returns <strong>14</strong> scripts that read+write its stateful queued / claims / capacity state files
  through a <code>join(ROOT, …)</code> on that dir (<code>we:scripts/check-standards.mjs:1484</code> is a
  representative read of <code>we:.claude/skills/batch-backlog-items/claims.json</code>). They resolve
  through a symlink in principle, but the state-file semantics (the local-signal carve-out that "never
  pushes") plus the count make skills a genuinely riskier, separately-gated migration than memory.
</p>

<h2>Verdict — a validation gate, not a fork</h2>
<p>
  The 2026-07-04 skeptic pass reclassified this. <strong>"Adopt vs keep <code>.claude</code>" is not a
  two-branch fork</strong>: keeping <code>.claude</code> + <code>--dangerously-skip-permissions</code> is the
  null/do-nothing baseline (and the flag is <em>always</em> the no-hook fallback), so it does not mutually
  exclude adopting — the real question is one-sided (<em>is the relocation+hook candidate worth building at
  all?</em>). The scope question (memory-only vs skills-later) collapses to a deferred config dimension
  (cost/frequency, not merit). So this carries a single verdict, not forks.
</p>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Verdict</th><th>Default now</th><th>Un-gate when</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>NOT-YET</strong></td>
      <td>Keep <code>.claude</code>; launch unattended runs with <code>--dangerously-skip-permissions</code>
        (interactive edits keep the one-click gate)</td>
      <td>(1) the per-click / all-or-nothing-bypass cost is <em>measured</em>; (2) the hook is scoped to
        design out the guard-lane self-deny + mis-fire + clobber hazards; (3) the <code>:2488</code> statute
        re-anchoring is specced into the adopting change</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<p>
  <strong>Decisive hazard.</strong> The redirect hook and <code>we:scripts/guard-lane.mjs</code> are
  <em>both</em> <code>PreToolUse</code> hooks, so the rewrite to <code>we:agent-memory-src</code> self-denies
  the interactive memory edit in the primary tree (<code>inPrimary &amp;&amp; !inLane &amp;&amp;
  !inAgentMemory</code> → exit 2) unless <code>guard-lane.mjs:56</code> is widened first — the migration is
  an order-sensitive coupling, not "just add a hook."
</p>

